{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a5d180b1b6f76946", "type": "tool_result", "content": "  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.12725v1: Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Karystinaios, Emmanouil\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.12725\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.12725\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Neural audio codecs were originally developed for high-fidelity compression; however, their latent token representations and expressive decoders also constitute a powerful substrate for controllable audio transformation. This work introduces Neural Morphing, a training-free token-domain audio effect that selects residual-vector-quantized (RVQ) token grains from a user palette and decodes the edited stream through a pretrained codec. The method combines an RVQ-group transfer policy that separates coarse, middle, and fine codebook groups with a continuity-constrained sequence matcher that replaces independent greedy selection with bounded beam search. The intended output is a controlled hybrid: the source preserves rhythmic organization while the palette contributes timbral color and residual detail. We focus on the implementation and realtime behavior of a deployable VST3/AU system, including chunked rendering, palette-size scaling, and backend health checks.\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Karystinaios,+E\" rel=\"nofollow\">Emmanouil Karystinaios</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs, by Emmanouil Karystinaios</div>\n    <a class=\"mobile-submission-download\" href=\"/pdf/2607.12725v1\">View PDF</a>\n    <a class=\"mobile-submission-download\" href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.12725v1\">HTML (experimental)</a>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Neural audio codecs were originally developed for high-fidelity compression; however, their latent token representations and expressive decoders also constitute a powerful substrate for controllable audio transformation. This work introduces Neural Morphing, a training-free token-domain audio effect that selects residual-vector-quantized (RVQ) token grains from a user palette and decodes the edited stream through a pretrained codec. The method combines an RVQ-group transfer policy that separates coarse, middle, and fine codebook groups with a continuity-constrained sequence matcher that replaces independent greedy selection with bounded beam search. The intended output is a controlled hybrid: the source preserves rhythmic organization while the palette contributes timbral color and residual detail. We focus on the implementation and realtime behavior of a deployable VST3/AU system, including chunked rendering, palette-size scaling, and backend health checks.\n  <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>\nView a PDF of the paper titled Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs, by Emmanouil Karystinaios</div><li><a href=\"/pdf/2607.12725v1\" aria-describedby=\"download-button-info\" accesskey=\"f\" class=\"abs-button download-pdf\">View PDF</a></li><li><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.12725v1\" class=\"abs-button\" id=\"latexml-download-link\">HTML (experimental)</a></li><li><a href=\"/src/2607.12725v1\" class=\"abs-button download-eprint\">TeX Source", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "515672ea-b0e3-4099-8b3a-cb1374ba7674", "uuid": "60f8f9aa-5f55-481e-99e4-8c909a9b51ee", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T08:03:05.068Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.12725v1: Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Karystinaios, Emmanouil\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/14\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.12725\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.12725\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Neural audio codecs were originally developed for high-fidelity compression; however, their latent token representations and expressive decoders also constitute a powerful substrate for controllable audio transformation. This work introduces Neural Morphing, a training-free token-domain audio effect that selects residual-vector-quantized (RVQ) token grains from a user palette and decodes the edited stream through a pretrained codec. The method combines an RVQ-group transfer policy that separates coarse, middle, and fine codebook groups with a continuity-constrained sequence matcher that replaces independent greedy selection with bounded beam search. The intended output is a controlled hybrid: the source preserves rhythmic organization while the palette contributes timbral color and residual detail. We focus on the implementation and realtime behavior of a deployable VST3/AU system, including chunked rendering, palette-size scaling, and backend health checks.\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Karystinaios,+E\" rel=\"nofollow\">Emmanouil Karystinaios</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled Neural Morphing: Sequence-Optimized Token-Level Morphing in Neural Audio Codecs, by Emmanouil Karystinaios</div>\n    <a class=\"mobile-submission-download\" href=\"/pdf/2607.12725v1\">View PDF</a>\n    <a class=\"mobile-submission-download\" href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.12725v1\">HTML (experimental)</a>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Neural audio codecs were originally developed for high-fidelity compression; however, their latent token representations and expressive decoders also constitute a powerful substrate for controllable audio transformation. This work introduces Neural Morphing, a training-free token-domain audio effect that selects residual-vector-quantized (RVQ) token grains from a user palette and decodes the edited stream through a pretrained codec. The method combines an RVQ-group transfer policy that separates coarse, middle, and fine codebook groups with a continuity-constrained sequence matcher that replaces independent greedy selection with bounded beam search. The intended output is a controlled hybrid: the source preserves rhythmic organization while the palette contributes timbral color and residual detail. We focus on the implementation and realtime behavior of a deployable VST3/AU system, including chunked rendering, palette-size scaling, and backend health checks.\n  <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>\nView a PDF of 